{"title_page": "Battle of Chalgrove Field", "text_new": "{{short description|First English Civil War, 1643}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Chalgrove Field\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| date        = 18 June 1643\n| place       =[[Chalgrove]], [[Oxfordshire]]\n| result      = Royalist victory\n| image       = Hampden monument - geograph.org.uk - 1011652.jpg\n| caption     = Monument to John Hampden on the battlefield, erected in 1843\n| combatant1 = {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2 = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = {{unbulleted list|{{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] |{{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Thomas_Wentworth,_5th_Baron_Wentworth|Lord Wentworth]] |{{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[William_Legge_(Royalist)|William Legge]] |{{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} Sir Henry Lunsford {{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=348}} }}\n| commander2  = {{unbulleted list|{{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} Sir [[Philip Stapleton]] |{{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[John Hampden]] {{KIA}} |{{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} John Gunter {{KIA}} |{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[John_Dalbier|Colonel Dalbier]] }}\n| strength1   = 1,150 cavalry; <br> 350 dragoons <br> 500 infantry {{sfn|Battlefield Trust|2008}}\n| strength2   = 900 cavalry (200 engaged); <br> 100 dragoons  \n| casualties1 = 20-45 (estimate)\n| casualties2 = max 50, unknown prisoners\n}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\nThe '''Battle of Chalgrove Field''' took place on 18 June 1643, during the [[First English Civil War]], near [[Chalgrove]], [[Oxfordshire]]. A relatively minor battle, it is best remembered for the death of [[John Hampden]], who died of wounds six days later.     \n\nRiding through the night of 17 to 18 June, [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cavalry under [[Prince Rupert]] raided [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] positions around [[Chinnor]]. As they returned to [[Oxford]], they were pursued by cavalry under Hampden and Major John Gunter; at [[Chalgrove]], Rupert led a counter attack, which scattered his opponents before the main force arrived under Sir [[Philip Stapleton]]; in the course of this, Hampden was wounded.  \n\nCombined with his failure to capitalise on the [[Siege_of_Reading|capture of Reading]], the defeat led to criticism of the   [[Robert_Devereux,_3rd_Earl_of_Essex|Earl of Essex]], commander of the Parliamentary army. It provided a significant boost to Royalist morale.  \n\n==Background==\n{{Location map many|Oxfordshire |caption = Oxfordshire, June 1643|relief=yes|border = black| width = 280| float = left\n|label =  Chalgrove|pos=bottom|lat_deg= 51.685|lon_deg = -1.077\n|label2 = Reading|pos2=right|lat2_deg= 51|lat2_min= 29|lon2_deg = 0 |lon2_min = -58\n|label3 = Thame |pos3= top|lat3_deg=51|lat3_min = 45|lon3_deg = 0|lon3_min = -59\n|label4 = Chinnor|pos4=bottom|lat4_deg=51|lat4_min = 42|lon4_deg = 0|lon4_min = -52\n|label5 = Oxford|pos5=left|lat5_deg=51|lat5_min =45 |lon5_deg = -1 |lon5_min = -16\n|label6 = Postcombe|pos6=top|lat6_deg=51.692|lon6_deg = -0.973\n|label7 = Chiselhampton|pos7=left|lat7_deg=51.685|lon7_deg = -1.143\n|label8 = Islip|pos8=left|lat8_deg=51.8 |lon8_deg =-1.23\n|label9 = Wycombe|pos9=left|lat9_deg=51.62 |lon9_deg =-0.74\n}} \nWhen the war began, both sides had expected a single, decisive battle, but the events of 1642 showed the need to plan for a lengthy conflict. For the Royalists, this meant fortifying their new capital in [[Oxford]], and connecting areas of support in England and Wales; Parliament focused on consolidating control of the areas they already held. Although [[Treaty_of_Oxford|peace talks]] were held in February, neither party did so with any conviction, and continued negotiations for third party support.{{sfn|Royle|2004|pp=208-209}} \n\nOrdered to take Oxford, the main Parliamentary field army under the [[Robert_Devereux,_3rd_Earl_of_Essex|Earl of Essex]] [[Siege_of_Reading|captured Reading]] on 27 April. Here he remained until mid May, when he went to [[London]], claiming he was unable to advance without additional supplies, and \u00a3100,000 in cash.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=217-218}} In response, a convoy was despatched in June, which included \u00a321,000 to pay the soldiers.{{sfn|Historic England 1000006}}\n\nOn 17 June, Essex sent 2,500 men to attack an outpost at [[Islip, Oxfordshire|Islip]], but they arrived to find the Royalists waiting, and retreated. In the course of this, Scots mercenary [[John_Urry_(soldier)|Sir John Hurry]] defected, taking with him news of the convoy, and details of Parliamentary troop positions.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=347}} \n\nSeeing an opportunity to respond, [[Prince Rupert of the Rhine|Prince Rupert]] left Oxford at 16:00 with 1,200 cavalry, 350 [[dragoons]], and 500 infantry. Hurry's information revealed Essex had concentrated his troops in the north, to protect the convoy, leaving his southern positions exposed. [[John Hampden]] was concerned by the possibility of such a raid, and checked his [[Picket_(military)|pickets]] before going to bed at 1:00 am.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=349}}           \n\nMany of the Parliamentary troops at [[Chinnor]] and [[Postcombe]] had just returned from the abortive attempt on Islip, and were exhausted; they failed to post guards, and were taken by surprise when the Royalists attacked at 5:30 am. Having inflicted 50 casualties, as well as capturing prisoners and stores, Prince Rupert decided to withdraw before his line of retreat was cut; by 6:30 am, his forces were on the road back to Oxford.{{sfn|Royle|2004|p=229}} \n\nWhile three troops under Hampden and Major John Gunter maintained contact with the Royalists, the local commander at [[Thame]], Sir [[Philip Stapleton]], hastily pulled together a force to attack them. Several senior officers, supposedly in Thame to collect their regiments' wages, helped him form a number of [[ad hoc]] units; having collected around 700 men, Stapleton set out in pursuit.{{sfn|Lester|Lester|2015|p=34}}\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:The Bridleway to Chalgrove - geograph.org.uk - 93360.jpg|thumb|right|Route taken by the Royalist infantry along the bridleway from Golder Hill to [[Easington, South Oxfordshire|Easington]]]]\nWith Sir Henry Lunsford's infantry leading the way, the Royalists made slow progress due to their prisoners and loot, with their column spread out along two miles. By 8:30 am, the rearguard was in contact with Hampden and Gunter, who had been joined by 100 dragoons under [[John_Dalbier|Colonel Dalbier]], an experienced German mercenary. Realising he could not outrun his pursuers, Rupert ordered Lunsford to keep moving, and secure the bridge at [[Chiselhampton]].{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=348}} \n\nThis took them along a bridleway, bounded by a \u2018Great Hedge\u2019, a double line of thick, shoulder-high hedgerows that could not be flanked. [[Thomas_Wentworth,_5th_Baron_Wentworth|Lord Wentworth]]'s dragoons set up an ambush further along the hedgerow (see Map), while Rupert's cavalry formed up in an open field. By now, the Parliamentary forces consisted of around 200 cavalry, plus the dragoons.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=349}}\n\nDalbier moved his dragoons up to the hedge, and opened fire on the Royalist cavalry; this prompted Prince Rupert into an attack, allegedly leaping the hedge while the rest of his men made their way around. Dalbier withdrew, reinforced by Hampden and Gunter; the Parliamentary troops initially held their ground, but were heavily outnumbered, and broke. For once, Rupert's men halted their pursuit, probably since their horses were exhausted, and withdrew to Chiselhampton, where they remained until the next day.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|pp=351-353}}   \n[[File:Chalgrove Battle Map.png|thumb|left|Chalgrove Battle Map]]\nMost accounts indicate that by the time Stapleton arrived, the fighting was largely over, although it has been suggested otherwise, primarily by Royalist statesman and historian, the [[Edward_Hyde,_1st_Earl_of_Clarendon|Earl of Clarendon]].{{sfn|Clarendon|1704|pp=262-263}} The claim that Parliamentary casualties contained a disproportionate number of senior officers also originated with Clarendon.{{sfn|Historic England|2020}}\n   \nCasualty figures are unclear, partly because contemporary reports often fail to distinguish between those incurred at Chinnor, the skirmish with the rearguard, and the battle itself. The Royalists reported a total of 45 for both sides, Essex suggested 50 each, including Gunter, who was killed close to the hedge, and Hampden. Shot twice in the shoulder, the wound became infected, and he died six days later. Later claims that his injuries were caused by the explosion of his own pistol have not been substantiated.{{sfn|Lester|Blackshaw|2000|pp=21-24}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn February, [[Queen Henrietta Maria]] landed in [[Bridlington|Bridlington, Yorkshire]] with an arms consignment from the [[Dutch Republic]]. By mid-June, the convoy was at [[Newark-on-Trent]]; Chalgrove ended any hopes of an interception, and it entered Oxford in early July. More importantly, the Royalists established a psychological edge over their opponents, confirmed on 25 June when Hurry attacked [[High_Wycombe|Wycombe]]. Essex withdrew from [[Oxfordshire]], allowing Prince Rupert to support operations in the west, culminating in the [[Storming_of_Bristol|capture of Bristol]] on 26 July.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=233-234}}\n\nArguably the greatest loss was that of Hampden; his close friend [[Anthony Nicholl]] wrote; \u2018Never Kingdom received a greater loss in one subject, never a man a truer and more faithful friend.\u2019{{sfn|Adair|1979|p=17}} His reputation for honesty and patriotism, and man management skills, had been vital in minimising internal divisions, particularly after the exposure of [[Edmund_Waller#'Waller's_Plot'|Edmund Waller's Plot]] on 31 May, with his links to many Parliamentary leaders, including Essex.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|p=219}} [[John Pym]]'s death in December meant the two most prominent leaders of the pre-war opposition disappeared from the scene in less than six months, in a period that proved the highpoint of Royalist success.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|p=278}}\n\nFollowing an extensive debate over whether it constituted a 'battle' or 'skirmish', [[English Heritage]] designated it a [[Registered Battlefields (UK)|registered battlefield]] in 1995.{{sfn|Historic England 1000006}} In 1843, [[George_Nugent-Grenville,_2nd_Baron_Nugent|George Nugent-Grenville]], a [[Radical_Whigs|Whig radical]] politician and author of the hagiographic ''Memorials of John Hampden'', paid for the Hampden Monument, located 700 metres south of the main site.{{sfn|Historic England 1059742}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes}}\n::{{cite journal |last1=Adair |first1=John |title=The Death of John Hampden |journal=History Today |date=1979 |volume=29 |issue=10 |ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book |last1=Clarendon |first1=Earl of |title=The History of the Rebellion and Civil Wars in England; Volume II |date=1704 |publisher=Wentworth Press |isbn=978-0469445765|ref=harv|edition=2019}}\n::{{NHLE |num=1059742 |desc=Hampden Monument |grade=II |accessdate=16 December 2015|mode=cs2}}\n::{{NHLE |num=1000006 |desc=Battle of Chalgrove 1643 |accessdate=11 April 2020|mode=cs2}}\n::{{cite web |title=Battle of Chalgrove 1643 |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1000006 |website=Historic England |accessdate=8 April 2020|ref=CITEREFHistoric_England2020}}\n::{{cite book |last=Lester |first=Derek |last2=Blackshaw |first2=Gill |year=2000|title=The Controversy of John Hampden\u2019s Death |publisher=Chalgrove Battle Group |isbn=978-0953803408|ref=harv}}\n::{{Cite journal|last1=Lester|first1=Derek|last2=Lester|first2=Gill|journal=Oxoniensia|volume=80|date=Dec 2015|title=The military and political importance of the battle of Chalgrove 1643|ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Royle|first=Trevor|year=2004|edition=2006|title=Civil War: The Wars of the Three Kingdoms 1638\u20131660|publisher=Abacus|isbn=978-0-349-11564-1}}     \n::{{cite journal|last1=Stevenson |first1=John |last2=Carter |first2=Andrew |year=1973 |title=The Raid on Chinnor and the Fight at Chalgrove Field |journal=Oxoniensia |publisher=Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society |volume=XXXVIII |ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book|last1=Wedgwood|first1=CV|title=The King's War, 1641-1647|date=1958|publisher=Penguin Classics|isbn=978-0141390727|ref=harv|edition=2001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chalgrove Field, Battle of}}\n[[Category:1643 in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1643]]\n[[Category:Military history of Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Registered historic battlefields in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|First English Civil War, 1643}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Chalgrove Field\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| date        = 18 June 1643\n| place       =[[Chalgrove]], [[Oxfordshire]]\n| result      = Royalist victory\n| image       = Hampden monument - geograph.org.uk - 1011652.jpg\n| caption     = Monument to John Hampden on the battlefield, erected in 1843\n| combatant1 = {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2 = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = {{unbulleted list|{{flagicon image|Royal