ided a significant boost to Royalist morale.  \n\n==Background==\n{{Location map many|Oxfordshire |caption = Oxfordshire, June 1643|relief=yes|border = black| width = 280| float = left\n|label =  Chalgrove|pos=bottom|lat_deg= 51.685|lon_deg = -1.077\n|label2 = Reading|pos2=right|lat2_deg= 51|lat2_min= 29|lon2_deg = 0 |lon2_min = -58\n|label3 = Thame |pos3= top|lat3_deg=51|lat3_min = 45|lon3_deg = 0|lon3_min = -59\n|label4 = Chinnor|pos4=bottom|lat4_deg=51|lat4_min = 42|lon4_deg = 0|lon4_min = -52\n|label5 = Oxford|pos5=left|lat5_deg=51|lat5_min =45 |lon5_deg = -1 |lon5_min = -16\n|label6 = Postcombe|pos6=top|lat6_deg=51.692|lon6_deg = -0.973\n|label7 = Chiselhampton|pos7=left|lat7_deg=51.685|lon7_deg = -1.143\n|label8 = Islip|pos8=left|lat8_deg=51.8 |lon8_deg =-1.23\n|label9 = Wycombe|pos9=left|lat9_deg=51.62 |lon9_deg =-0.74\n}} \nWhen the war began, both sides had expected a single, decisive battle, but the events of 1642 showed the need to plan for a lengthy conflict. For the Royalists, this meant fortifying their new capital in [[Oxford]], and connecting areas of support in England and Wales; Parliament focused on consolidating control of the areas they already held. Although [[Treaty_of_Oxford|peace talks]] were held in February, neither party did so with any conviction, and continued negotiations for third party support.{{sfn|Royle|2004|pp=208-209}} \n\nOrdered to take Oxford, the main Parliamentary field army under the [[Robert_Devereux,_3rd_Earl_of_Essex|Earl of Essex]] [[Siege_of_Reading|captured Reading]] on 27 April. Here he remained until mid May, when he went to [[London]], claiming he was unable to advance without additional supplies, and \u00a3100,000 in cash.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=217-218}} In response, a convoy was despatched in June, which included \u00a321,000 to pay the soldiers.{{sfn|Historic England 1000006}}\n\nOn 17 June, Essex sent 2,500 men to attack an outpost at [[Islip, Oxfordshire|Islip]], but they arrived to find the Royalists waiting,