rd was in contact with Hampden and Gunter, who had been joined by 100 dragoons under [[John_Dalbier|Colonel Dalbier]], an experienced German mercenary. Realising he could not outrun his pursuers, Rupert ordered Lunsford to keep moving, and secure the bridge at [[Chiselhampton]].{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=348}} \n\nThis took them along a bridleway, bounded by a \u2018Great Hedge\u2019, a double line of thick, shoulder-high hedgerows that could not be flanked. [[Thomas_Wentworth,_5th_Baron_Wentworth|Lord Wentworth]]'s dragoons set up an ambush further along the hedgerow (see Map), while Rupert's cavalry formed up in an open field. By now, the Parliamentary forces consisted of around 200 cavalry, plus the dragoons.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|p=349}}\n\nDalbier moved his dragoons up to the hedge, and opened fire on the Royalist cavalry; this prompted Prince Rupert into an attack, allegedly leaping the hedge while the rest of his men made their way around. Dalbier withdrew, reinforced by Hampden and Gunter; the Parliamentary troops initially held their ground, but were heavily outnumbered, and broke. For once, Rupert's men halted their pursuit, probably since their horses were exhausted, and withdrew to Chiselhampton, where they remained until the next day.{{sfn|Stevenson|Carter|1973|pp=351-353}}   \n[[File:Chalgrove Battle Map.png|thumb|left|Chalgrove Battle Map]]\nMost accounts indicate that by the time Stapleton arrived, the fighting was largely over, although it has been suggested otherwise, primarily by Royalist statesman and historian, the [[Edward_Hyde,_1st_Earl_of_Clarendon|Earl of Clarendon]].{{sfn|Clarendon|1704|pp=262-263}} The claim that Parliamentary casualties contained a disproportionate number of senior officers also originated with Clarendon.{{sfn|Historic England|2020}}\n   \nCasualty figures are unclear, partly because contemporary reports often fail to distinguish between those incurred at Chinnor, the skirmish with the rearguard, and the battle itself. The Royalists reported a total of 45 for both sides, Essex suggested 50 each, including Gunter, who was killed close to the hedge, and Hampden. Shot twice in the shoulder, the wound became infected, and he died six days later. Later claims that his injuries were caused by the explosion of his own pistol have not been substantiated.{{sfn|Lester|Blackshaw|2000|pp=21-24}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn February, [[Queen Henrietta Maria]] landed in [[Bridlington|Bridlington, Yorkshire]] with an arms consignment from the [[Dutch Republic]]. By mid-June, the convoy was at [[Newark-on-Trent]]; Chalgrove ended any hopes of an interception, and it entered Oxford in early July. More importantly, the Royalists established a psychological edge over their opponents, confirmed on 25 June when Hurry attacked [[High_Wycombe|Wycombe]]. Essex withdrew from [[Oxfordshire]], allowing Prince Rupert to support operations in the west, culminating in the [[Storming_of_Bristol|capture of Bristol]] on 26 July.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|pp=233-234}}\n\nArguably the greatest loss was that of Hampden; his close friend [[Anthony Nicholl]] wrote; \u2018Never Kingdom received a greater loss in one subject, never a man a truer and more faithful friend.\u2019{{sfn|Adair|1979|p=17}} His reputation for honesty and patriotism, and man management skills, had been vital in minimising internal divisions, particularly after the exposure of [[Edmund_Waller#'Waller's_Plot'|Edmund Waller's Plot]] on 31 May, with his links to many Parliamentary leaders, including Essex.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|p=219}} [[John Pym]]'s death in December meant the two most prominent leaders of the pre-war opposition disappeared from the scene in less than six months, in a period that proved the highpoint of Royalist success.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1958|p=278}}\n\nFollowing an extensive debate over whether it constituted a 'battle' or 'skirmish', [[English Heritage]] designated it a [[Registered Battlefields (UK)|registered battlefield]] in 1995.{{sfn|Historic England 1000006}} In 1843, [[George_Nugent-Grenville,_2nd_Baron_Nugent|George Nugent-Grenville]], a [[Radical_Whigs|Whig radical]] politician and author of the hagiographic ''Memorials of John Hampden'', paid for the Hampden Monument, located 700 metres south of the main site.{{sfn|Historic England 1059742}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes}}\n::{{cite journal |last1=Adair |first1=John |title=The Death of John Hampden |journal=History Today |date=1979 |volume=29 |issue=10 |ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book |last1=Clarendon |first1=Earl of |title=The History of the Rebellion and Civil Wars in England; Volume II |date=1704 |publisher=Wentworth Press |isbn=978-0469445765|ref=harv|edition=2019}}\n::{{NHLE |num=1059742 |desc=Hampden Monument |grade=II |accessdate=16 December 2015|mode=cs2}}\n::{{NHLE |num=1000006 |desc=Battle of Chalgrove 1643 |accessdate=11 April 2020|mode=cs2}}\n::{{cite web |title=Battle of Chalgrove 1643 |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1000006 |website=Historic England |accessdate=8 April 2020|ref=CITEREFHistoric_England2020}}\n::{{cite book |last=Lester |first=Derek |last2=Blackshaw |first2=Gill |year=2000|title=The Controversy of John Hampden\u2019s Death |publisher=Chalgrove Battle Group |isbn=978-0953803408|ref=harv}}\n::{{Cite journal|last1=Lester|first1=Derek|last2=Lester|first2=Gill|journal=Oxoniensia|volume=80|date=Dec 2015|title=The military and political importance of the battle of Chalgrove 1643|ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Royle|first=Trevor|year=2004|edition=2006|title=Civil War: The Wars of the Three Kingdoms 1638\u20131660|publisher=Abacus|isbn=978-0-349-11564-1}}     \n::{{cite journal|last1=Stevenson |first1=John |last2=Carter |first2=Andrew |year=1973 |title=The Raid on Chinnor and the Fight at Chalgrove Field |journal=Oxoniensia |publisher=Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society |volume=XXXVIII |ref=harv}}\n::{{cite book|last1=Wedgwood|first1=CV|